<h2 id="cost">Cost &amp; Pricing</h2>

<div class="faq-item">
<h3>How much does it cost to wrap a car in Chicago?</h3>
<p>A full car wrap in Chicago runs <strong>$3,200–$4,800</strong> depending on the vehicle size and design complexity. Sedans and coupes are on the lower end, SUVs and crossovers on the higher end. This includes custom design, premium Avery Dennison or 3M cast vinyl, professional installation, and a 2-year workmanship warranty. Partial wraps and spot graphics start at $800–$2,500. Use our <a href="/calculator/">Wrap Calculator</a> for an instant estimate.</p>
</div>

<div class="faq-item">
<h3>How much does it cost to wrap a cargo van?</h3>
<p>A full wrap on a standard cargo van (Ford Transit, Ram ProMaster, Chevy Express) costs <strong>$3,750–$4,500</strong>. This is the most common vehicle we wrap for commercial clients — HVAC companies, plumbers, electricians, and delivery fleets. The price includes design, premium cast vinyl, installation, and warranty. Partial van wraps (sides and rear only) run $1,800–$2,800.</p>
</div>

<div class="faq-item">
<h3>How much does it cost to wrap a Sprinter van?</h3>
<p>Sprinter and high-roof van full wraps cost <strong>$4,700–$5,500</strong> due to the additional surface area and height. Mercedes Sprinters, Ford Transit high-roof, and Ram ProMaster high-roof all fall in this range. The extra height requires specialized equipment and more installation time (typically 2 full days). See our <a href="/sprinter/">Sprinter wrap page</a> for examples.</p>
</div>

<div class="faq-item">
<h3>How much does it cost to wrap a box truck?</h3>
<p>Box truck wraps depend on the truck size. A <strong>16–20 ft box truck</strong> full wrap costs <strong>$5,000–$6,500</strong>. A <strong>22–26 ft box truck</strong> runs <strong>$6,500–$8,500</strong>. The flat sides of box trucks are actually easier to wrap than curved vans, but the sheer surface area drives the cost. See our <a href="/boxtruck/">box truck wrap page</a> for pricing details and examples.</p>
</div>

