<div class="faq-item">
<h3>Is it cheaper to wrap a car or paint it?</h3>
<p>Wrapping is significantly cheaper. A quality commercial paint job runs <strong>$5,000–$15,000+</strong>. A full vinyl wrap costs <strong>$3,200–$6,500</strong> depending on vehicle size — that is 30–50% less than paint. But cost is not the only advantage: wraps protect the original paint, are fully removable, and can be changed when you rebrand. Paint is permanent and can hurt resale value if the color is non-standard. For commercial vehicles, wraps win on every metric.</p>
</div>

<div class="faq-item">
<h3>Are vehicle wraps tax deductible?</h3>
<p>Yes. Commercial vehicle wraps qualify as advertising expenses under <strong>IRS Section 179</strong> — 100% deductible in the year of purchase. A $4,000 van wrap in the 28% federal tax bracket has an after-tax cost of approximately $2,880. This makes wraps one of the most cost-effective marketing investments available to small businesses. Consult your CPA for your specific situation.</p>
</div>

<div class="faq-item">
<h3>What is included in the price of a vehicle wrap?</h3>
<p>Every Chicago Fleet Wraps quote includes: design consultation, custom artwork creation, 1–2 rounds of revisions, premium cast vinyl material (Avery Dennison or 3M), UV-protective overlaminate, professional installation in our climate-controlled bay, post-install quality inspection, and a 2-year workmanship warranty. Free pickup and delivery within our 50-mile service area is always included for fleet clients.</p>
</div>

<div class="faq-item">
<h3>How much do vinyl lettering and decals cost?</h3>
<p>Basic vinyl lettering (company name, phone number, website) starts at <strong>$300–$600</strong> per vehicle. More complex decal packages with logos, graphics, and DOT numbers run <strong>$600–$1,200</strong>. Lettering is a budget-friendly option for businesses that want professional identification without the investment of a full wrap. It can also be combined with a partial wrap for maximum impact at a moderate price point.</p>
</div>

