<h2 id="paint">Paint, Damage &amp; Removal</h2>

<div class="faq-item">
<h3>Will a vehicle wrap damage my paint?</h3>
<p>No. Premium cast vinyl (Avery Dennison, 3M) applied and removed correctly does <strong>not damage factory paint</strong>. The wrap actually protects paint from UV fading, rock chips, and road debris. Chicago Fleet Wraps has completed 9,400+ wraps with zero verified paint damage claims. The key factors are: using cast (not calendered) vinyl, professional installation, and professional removal. Aftermarket paint, Maaco-type repaints, and touch-up paint may react differently — we assess this during vehicle intake.</p>
</div>

<div class="faq-item">
<h3>What is the downside of wrapping a car?</h3>
<p>Honest answer: wraps are not permanent and do require some care. The main considerations are: (1) Wraps last 5–7 years, not forever — they will eventually need replacement. (2) You cannot use automatic brush car washes. (3) Wraps will not hide existing paint damage — dents, rust, and peeling clear coat show through. (4) Low-quality wraps (calendered vinyl from budget shops) can damage paint and look terrible within a year. The solution to #4 is using a reputable shop that uses cast vinyl — which is what we do exclusively.</p>
</div>

<div class="faq-item">
<h3>Can a wrap be removed? How much does removal cost?</h3>
<p>Yes, wraps are designed for clean removal. Using controlled heat (heat gun) and proper technique, the vinyl peels away leaving the original paint intact. Professional removal costs <strong>$500–$1,500</strong> depending on vehicle size and the condition of the existing wrap. Older wraps (7+ years) and wraps that were installed poorly take longer to remove. We offer removal as a standalone service — you do not need to be getting a new wrap.</p>
</div>

<div class="faq-item">
<h3>Can you wrap a vehicle with existing paint damage, rust, or dents?</h3>
<p>It depends on the severity. Minor scratches and light oxidation can usually be wrapped over. However, <strong>rust, peeling clear coat, deep scratches, and body damage should be repaired first</strong>. Vinyl conforms to the surface underneath — it does not fill or hide imperfections, it telegraphs them. We inspect every vehicle during intake and will let you know if any bodywork is needed before wrapping.</p>
</div>

<div class="faq-item">
<h3>Does the wrap protect against scratches and rock chips?</h3>
<p>Yes, to a degree. Vinyl wrap acts as a sacrificial layer that absorbs minor scratches, rock chips, and road debris that would otherwise damage paint. It is not as thick as dedicated paint protection film (PPF/clear bra), but it provides meaningful everyday protection — especially valuable for fleet vehicles in commercial use. For maximum protection, we also offer <a href="/ceramic-coating-chicago/">ceramic coating</a> over wraps.</p>
</div>

