<h2 id="care">Wrap Care &amp; Maintenance</h2>

<div class="faq-item">
<h3>Can a wrapped car go through a car wash?</h3>
<p><strong>Touchless car washes: yes.</strong> Automatic car washes with spinning brushes: no. The brushes can scratch the vinyl surface and lift edges over time. Hand washing with mild automotive soap and water is the best method and will keep your wrap looking new for years. See our <a href="/care/">Wrap Care Guide</a> for detailed instructions.</p>
</div>

<div class="faq-item">
<h3>How do I wash and maintain my vehicle wrap?</h3>
<p>The basics:</p>
<ul>
<li><strong>Hand wash</strong> with mild soap (dish soap works) and water. Use a soft sponge or microfiber cloth.</li>
<li><strong>Pressure washer</strong> is OK but keep below 1,200 PSI, hold 12+ inches from the surface, and spray at an indirect angle — never directly at seams or edges.</li>
<li><strong>No wax</strong> on matte or satin finishes. Gloss wraps can be waxed with wrap-safe products.</li>
<li><strong>Bird droppings, tree sap, fuel spills</strong> — clean within 24 hours to prevent staining.</li>
<li><strong>Winter salt</strong> — rinse off road salt regularly. It will not damage the vinyl but can build up in panel gaps.</li>
</ul>
</div>

<div class="faq-item">
<h3>How do I protect my vehicle wrap in winter?</h3>
<p>Chicago winters are hard on everything, but wraps handle them well. Key tips: (1) Rinse road salt off weekly — it does not damage vinyl but buildup in panel gaps can cause lifting. (2) Never use ice scrapers on wrapped surfaces — use a soft snow brush. (3) Avoid automatic brush car washes (this applies year-round). (4) If possible, park in a garage. (5) Our cast vinyl is rated for -20°F and handles Chicago freeze-thaw cycles without shrinking. We have 24+ years of wraps surviving Chicago winters.</p>
</div>

<div class="faq-item">
<h3>Do wraps fade in the sun?</h3>
<p>Quality wraps with UV-protective overlaminate resist fading for 5–7 years. The Avery Dennison DOL 1460 overlaminate we use on every printed wrap blocks UV radiation that causes color degradation. That said, a wrap parked in direct sun 12 hours a day in Arizona will fade faster than one garaged in Chicago. Parking in shade when possible extends the life of any wrap.</p>
</div>

