<h2 id="roi">ROI &amp; Business Value</h2>

<div class="faq-item">
<h3>How many daily impressions does a wrapped vehicle generate?</h3>
<p>The Outdoor Advertising Association of America (OAAA) documents <strong>30,000–70,000 daily impressions</strong> per wrapped vehicle. In Chicago's Cook County metro, service vans on regular residential routes typically generate 50,000+ daily impressions — approximately <strong>87 million over a 6-year wrap lifespan</strong>. No other advertising medium delivers this volume at this cost.</p>
</div>

<div class="faq-item">
<h3>Is wrapping your company vehicle worth it?</h3>
<p>The numbers speak for themselves. A $4,000 van wrap generates 50,000+ daily impressions for 6+ years. That is 87+ million impressions at a cost of <strong>$0.04 per thousand impressions</strong>. Compare that to Google Ads ($6–$12 per thousand), Facebook Ads ($5–$8 per thousand), or newspaper ads ($3.56 per impression). Plus, the wrap is tax deductible under IRS Section 179 and protects your vehicle's paint. The ROI is 2,500–5,000% over the wrap's lifespan. Use our <a href="/roi/">ROI Calculator</a> for your specific numbers.</p>
</div>

<div class="faq-item">
<h3>Does wrapping increase a vehicle's resale value?</h3>
<p>Indirectly, yes. Wraps protect the original paint from UV damage, scratches, and wear. When the wrap is removed at resale time, the paint underneath is in better condition than an unwrapped vehicle of the same age. This can increase resale value by <strong>10–15%</strong> compared to a vehicle with worn or sun-damaged paint. For leased vehicles, this means no paint condition deductions at lease return.</p>
</div>

<div class="faq-item">
<h3>How does a wrap compare to magnetic signs?</h3>
<p>Magnetic signs are cheaper upfront ($200–$500) but have significant drawbacks: they cover only small areas, can scratch paint from trapped debris, blow off at highway speeds, and look unprofessional. A full wrap covers the entire vehicle, generates <strong>5–10x more impressions</strong>, projects a premium brand image 24/7, and doubles as paint protection. For any business serious about branding, wraps are the clear winner.</p>
</div>

<div class="faq-item">
<h3>What information should I include on my fleet wrap?</h3>
<p>At minimum: company name, logo, phone number, and website. Beyond that, the most effective fleet wraps include: a clear description of services (not just your industry — tell people what you do), your service area, and a strong visual that catches attention from 50+ feet away. Avoid cluttering the design with too much text — drivers have 3–5 seconds to absorb your message. Our design team specializes in high-impact fleet graphics that convert impressions into calls.</p>
</div>

