<h2 id="chicago">Chicago-Specific Questions</h2>

<div class="faq-item">
<h3>How do Chicago winters affect vehicle wraps?</h3>
<p>Chicago's freeze-thaw cycles and road salt are tough on low-quality vinyl — but cast vinyl handles it. Avery Dennison and 3M cast vinyl is rated for <strong>-20°F to 100°F</strong> without shrinking, cracking, or lifting. Road salt does not damage vinyl — just rinse it off regularly to prevent buildup in panel gaps. Our wraps regularly last 6–7 years through Chicago winters. We have 24+ years of data proving this in real-world Chicago conditions.</p>
</div>

<div class="faq-item">
<h3>Is your shop climate-controlled?</h3>
<p>Yes. Our installation bay at 4711 N Lamon Ave is maintained at <strong>70°F year-round</strong>. Temperature is critical for vinyl adhesion — cold shops cause lifting and adhesion failure, hot shops cause overstretching. Our climate-controlled environment ensures consistent quality whether we are installing in January or July.</p>
</div>

<div class="faq-item">
<h3>Do you need a permit to drive a wrapped vehicle in Chicago?</h3>
<p>No. Wrapped vehicles do not require any special permits in Chicago or Illinois. Commercial vehicle wraps are classified as advertising and are fully legal on all roads, expressways, and toll roads. No city sticker, sign permit, or DOT filing is required for vinyl vehicle graphics. The only exception is if your vehicle requires commercial vehicle registration (based on weight class), which is unrelated to the wrap.</p>
</div>

